text:
.button {
    border: none;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-weight: medium;
    text-transform: lowercase;
    font-family: "Roboto", Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
    transition: background 0.2s;
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 8px;
}

.button::first-letter {
    text-transform: uppercase;
}

why doesn't this make the first letter in uppercase?
The issue might be that `text-transform: lowercase` is being applied after the `::first-letter` pseudo-element. CSS properties are applied in order of specificity and cascade, and in this case, the `text-transform: lowercase` on the entire button is overriding the `text-transform: uppercase` on the first letter.

To fix this, you have a few options:

1. Use a more specific selector for the first letter:
```css
.button {
    text-transform: lowercase;
}

.button::first-letter {
    text-transform: uppercase !important; /* Use with caution */
}
```

2. Remove `text-transform: lowercase` from the button and handle the case manually:
```css
.button {
    border: none;
    cursor: pointer;
    /* remove text-transform: lowercase */
}

/* Add this class to your text content */
.button .text {
    text-transform: lowercase;
}

.button .text::first-letter {
    text-transform: uppercase;
}
```

3. Consider using JavaScript to capitalize the first letter instead:
```javascript
const text = "your text";
const capitalizedText = text.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + text.slice(1).toLowerCase();
```

4. Or use CSS `text-transform: capitalize` instead, which will capitalize the first letter of each word:
```css
.button {
    text-transform: capitalize;
}
```

The most reliable solution would be option 2 or 3, as they give you the most control over the text transformation.
